155/*
156 * Flag bits in first flag field in connectionless PDU header.
157 */
158#define PFCL1_RESERVED_010x01 0x01 /* Reserved for use by implementations */
159#define PFCL1_LASTFRAG0x02 0x02 /* If set, the PDU is the last
160 * fragment of a multi-PDU
161 * transmission */
162#define PFCL1_FRAG0x04 0x04 /* If set, the PDU is a fragment of
163 a multi-PDU transmission */
164#define PFCL1_NOFACK0x08 0x08 /* If set, the receiver is not
165 * requested to send a `fack' PDU
166 * for the fragment */
167#define PFCL1_MAYBE0x10 0x10 /* If set, the PDU is for a `maybe'
168 * request */
169#define PFCL1_IDEMPOTENT0x20 0x20 /* If set, the PDU is for an idempotent
170 * request */
171#define PFCL1_BROADCAST0x40 0x40 /* If set, the PDU is for a broadcast
172 * request */
173#define PFCL1_RESERVED_800x80 0x80 /* Reserved for use by implementations */
174
175/*
176 * Flag bits in second flag field in connectionless PDU header.
177 */
178#define PFCL2_RESERVED_010x01 0x01 /* Reserved for use by implementations */
179#define PFCL2_CANCEL_PENDING0x02 0x02 /* Cancel pending at the call end */
180#define PFCL2_RESERVED_040x04 0x04 /* Reserved for future use */
181#define PFCL2_RESERVED_080x08 0x08 /* Reserved for future use */
182#define PFCL2_RESERVED_100x10 0x10 /* Reserved for future use */
183#define PFCL2_RESERVED_200x20 0x20 /* Reserved for future use */
184#define PFCL2_RESERVED_400x40 0x40 /* Reserved for future use */
185#define PFCL2_RESERVED_800x80 0x80 /* Reserved for future use */
186
187/*
188 * Flag bits in connection-oriented PDU header.
189 */
190#define PFC_FIRST_FRAG0x01 0x01 /* First fragment */
191#define PFC_LAST_FRAG0x02 0x02 /* Last fragment */
192#define PFC_PENDING_CANCEL0x04 0x04 /* Cancel was pending at sender */
193#define PFC_RESERVED_10x08 0x08
194#define PFC_CONC_MPX0x10 0x10 /* supports concurrent multiplexing
195 * of a single connection. */
196#define PFC_DID_NOT_EXECUTE0x20 0x20 /* only meaningful on `fault' packet;
197 * if true, guaranteed call did not
198 * execute. */
199#define PFC_MAYBE0x40 0x40 /* `maybe' call semantics requested */
200#define PFC_OBJECT_UUID0x80 0x80 /* if true, a non-nil object UUID
201 * was specified in the handle, and
202 * is present in the optional object
203 * field. If false, the object field
204 * is omitted. */
205
206/*
207 * Tests whether a connection-oriented PDU is fragmented; returns TRUE if
208 * it's not fragmented (i.e., this is both the first *and* last fragment),
209 * and FALSE otherwise.
210 */
211#define PFC_NOT_FRAGMENTED(hdr)((hdr->flags&(0x01|0x02)) == (0x01|0x02)) \
212 ((hdr->flags&(PFC_FIRST_FRAG0x01|PFC_LAST_FRAG0x02)) == (PFC_FIRST_FRAG0x01|PFC_LAST_FRAG0x02))
213

684static GSList *decode_dcerpc_bindings = NULL((void*)0);
685/*
686 * To keep track of ctx_id mappings.
687 *
688 * Every time we see a bind call we update this table.
689 * Note that we always specify a SMB FID. For non-SMB transports this
690 * value is 0.
691 */
692static GHashTable *dcerpc_binds = NULL((void*)0);
693
694typedef struct _dcerpc_bind_key {
695 conversation_t *conv;
696 guint16 ctx_id;
697 guint64 transport_salt;
698} dcerpc_bind_key;
699
700typedef struct _dcerpc_bind_value {
701 e_guid_t uuid;
702 guint16 ver;
703 e_guid_t transport;
704} dcerpc_bind_value;
705
706/* Extra data for DCERPC handling and tracking of context ids */
707typedef struct _dcerpc_decode_as_data {
708 guint16 dcectxid; /**< Context ID (DCERPC-specific) */
709 int dcetransporttype; /**< Transport type
710 * Value -1 means "not a DCERPC packet"
711 */
712 guint64 dcetransportsalt; /**< fid: if transporttype==DCE_CN_TRANSPORT_SMBPIPE */
713} dcerpc_decode_as_data;
714
715static dcerpc_decode_as_data*
716dcerpc_get_decode_data(packet_info* pinfo)
717{
718 dcerpc_decode_as_data* data = (dcerpc_decode_as_data*)p_get_proto_data(pinfo->pool, pinfo, proto_dcerpc, 0);
719 if (data == NULL((void*)0))
720 {
721 data = wmem_new0(pinfo->pool, dcerpc_decode_as_data)((dcerpc_decode_as_data*)wmem_alloc0((pinfo->pool), sizeof
(dcerpc_decode_as_data)));
722 data->dcetransporttype = -1;
723 p_add_proto_data(pinfo->pool, pinfo, proto_dcerpc, 0, data);
724 }
725
726 return data;
727}
728
729/**
730 * Registers a conversation/UUID binding association, so that
731 * we can invoke the proper sub-dissector for a given DCERPC
732 * conversation.
733 *
734 * @param binding all values needed to create and bind a new conversation
735 *
736 * @return Pointer to newly-added UUID/conversation binding.
737 */
738static struct _dcerpc_bind_value *
739dcerpc_add_conv_to_bind_table(decode_dcerpc_bind_values_t *binding)
740{
741 dcerpc_bind_value *bind_value;
742 dcerpc_bind_key *key;
743 conversation_t *conv;
744
745 conv = find_conversation(
746 0,
747 &binding->addr_a,
748 &binding->addr_b,
749 binding->ptype,
750 binding->port_a,
751 binding->port_b,
752 0);
753
754 if (!conv) {
755 conv = conversation_new(
756 0,
757 &binding->addr_a,
758 &binding->addr_b,
759 binding->ptype,
760 binding->port_a,
761 binding->port_b,
762 0);
763 }
764
765 bind_value = (dcerpc_bind_value *)wmem_alloc(wmem_file_scope(), sizeof (dcerpc_bind_value));
766 bind_value->uuid = binding->uuid;
767 bind_value->ver = binding->ver;
768 /* For now, assume all DCE/RPC we pick from "decode as" is using
769 standard ndr and not ndr64.
770 We should make this selectable from the dialog in the future
771 */
772 bind_value->transport = uuid_data_repr_proto;
773
774 key = (dcerpc_bind_key *)wmem_alloc(wmem_file_scope(), sizeof (dcerpc_bind_key));
775 key->conv = conv;
776 key->ctx_id = binding->ctx_id;
777 key->transport_salt = binding->transport_salt;
778
779 /* add this entry to the bind table */
780 g_hash_table_insert(dcerpc_binds, key, bind_value);
781
782 return bind_value;
783
784}
785
786/* inject one of our bindings into the dcerpc binding table */
787static void
788decode_dcerpc_inject_binding(gpointer data, gpointer user_data _U___attribute__((unused)))
789{
790 dcerpc_add_conv_to_bind_table((decode_dcerpc_bind_values_t *) data);
791}
792
793/* inject all of our bindings into the dcerpc binding table */
794static void
795decode_dcerpc_inject_bindings(void) {
796 g_slist_foreach(decode_dcerpc_bindings, decode_dcerpc_inject_binding, NULL((void*)0) /* user_data */);
797}

842
843static void
844dcerpc_prompt(packet_info *pinfo, gchar* result)
845{
846 GString *str = g_string_new("Replace binding between:\r\n"),
847 *address_str = g_string_new("");
848 dcerpc_decode_as_data* decode_data = dcerpc_get_decode_data(pinfo);
849
850 switch (pinfo->ptype) {
851 case(PT_TCP):
852 g_string_append(address_str, "Address: ToBeDone TCP port");
853 break;
854 case(PT_UDP):
855 g_string_append(address_str, "Address: ToBeDone UDP port");
856 break;
857 default:
858 g_string_append(address_str, "Address: ToBeDone Unknown port type");
859 }
860
861 g_string_append_printf(str, "%s: %u\r\n", address_str->str, pinfo->srcport);
862 g_string_append(str, "&\r\n");
863 g_string_append_printf(str, "%s: %u\r\n", address_str->str, pinfo->destport);
864 g_string_append_printf(str, "&\r\nContext ID: %u\r\n", decode_data->dcectxid);
865 g_string_append_printf(str, "&\r\nSMB FID: %"G_GINT64_MODIFIER"l""u\r\n",
866 dcerpc_get_transport_salt(pinfo));
867 g_string_append(str, "with:\r\n");
868
869 g_strlcpy(result, str->str, MAX_DECODE_AS_PROMPT_LEN200);
870 g_string_free(str, TRUE(!(0)));
871 g_string_free(address_str, TRUE(!(0)));
872}
873
874static gpointer
875dcerpc_value(packet_info *pinfo)
876{
877 decode_dcerpc_bind_values_t *binding;
878 dcerpc_decode_as_data* decode_data = dcerpc_get_decode_data(pinfo);
879
880 /* clone binding */
881 binding = g_new(decode_dcerpc_bind_values_t,1)(decode_dcerpc_bind_values_t *) (__extension__ ({ gsize __n =
(gsize) (1); gsize __s = sizeof (decode_dcerpc_bind_values_t
); gpointer __p; if (__s == 1) __p = g_malloc (__n); else if (
__builtin_constant_p (__n) && (__s == 0 || __n <= (
9223372036854775807L *2UL+1UL) / __s)) __p = g_malloc (__n * __s
); else __p = g_malloc_n (__n, __s); __p; }));
882 copy_address(&binding->addr_a, &pinfo->src);
883 copy_address(&binding->addr_b, &pinfo->dst);
884 binding->ptype = pinfo->ptype;
885 binding->port_a = pinfo->srcport;
886 binding->port_b = pinfo->destport;
887 binding->ctx_id = decode_data->dcectxid;
888 binding->transport_salt = dcerpc_get_transport_salt(pinfo);
889 binding->ifname = NULL((void*)0);
890 /*binding->uuid = NULL;*/
891 binding->ver = 0;
892
893 return binding;
894}
895
896struct dcerpc_decode_as_populate
897{
898 decode_as_add_to_list_func add_to_list;
899 gpointer ui_element;
900};
901
902static void
903decode_dcerpc_add_to_list(gpointer key, gpointer value, gpointer user_data)
904{
905 struct dcerpc_decode_as_populate* populate = (struct dcerpc_decode_as_populate*)user_data;
906
907 /*guid_key *k = key;*/
908 dcerpc_uuid_value *v = (dcerpc_uuid_value *)value;
909
910 if (strcmp(v->name, "(none)"))
911 populate->add_to_list("DCE-RPC", v->name, key, populate->ui_element);
912}
913
914static void
915dcerpc_populate_list(const gchar *table_name _U___attribute__((unused)), decode_as_add_to_list_func add_to_list, gpointer ui_element)
916{
917 struct dcerpc_decode_as_populate populate;
918
919 populate.add_to_list = add_to_list;
920 populate.ui_element = ui_element;
921
922 g_hash_table_foreach(dcerpc_uuids, decode_dcerpc_add_to_list, &populate);
923}
924
925/* compare two bindings (except the interface related things, e.g. uuid) */
926static gint
927decode_dcerpc_binding_cmp(gconstpointer a, gconstpointer b)
928{
929 const decode_dcerpc_bind_values_t *binding_a = (const decode_dcerpc_bind_values_t *)a;
930 const decode_dcerpc_bind_values_t *binding_b = (const decode_dcerpc_bind_values_t *)b;
931
932
933 /* don't compare uuid and ver! */
934 if (
935 addresses_equal(&binding_a->addr_a, &binding_b->addr_a) &&
936 addresses_equal(&binding_a->addr_b, &binding_b->addr_b) &&
937 binding_a->ptype == binding_b->ptype &&
938 binding_a->port_a == binding_b->port_a &&
939 binding_a->port_b == binding_b->port_b &&
940 binding_a->ctx_id == binding_b->ctx_id &&
941 binding_a->transport_salt == binding_b->transport_salt)
942 {
943 /* equal */
944 return 0;
945 }
946
947 /* unequal */
948 return 1;
949}
950
951/* remove a binding (looking the same way as the given one) */
952static gboolean
953decode_dcerpc_binding_reset(const char *name _U___attribute__((unused)), gconstpointer pattern)
954{
955 const decode_dcerpc_bind_values_t *binding = (const decode_dcerpc_bind_values_t *)pattern;
956 GSList *le;
957 decode_dcerpc_bind_values_t *old_binding;
958
959 /* find the old binding (if it exists) */
960 le = g_slist_find_custom(decode_dcerpc_bindings,
961 binding,
962 decode_dcerpc_binding_cmp);
963 if (le == NULL((void*)0))
964 return FALSE(0);
965
966 old_binding = (decode_dcerpc_bind_values_t *)le->data;
967
968 decode_dcerpc_bindings = g_slist_remove(decode_dcerpc_bindings, le->data);
969
970 free_address(&old_binding->addr_a);
971 free_address(&old_binding->addr_b);
972 g_string_free(old_binding->ifname, TRUE(!(0)));
973 g_free(old_binding);
974 return FALSE(0);
975}
976
977static gboolean
978dcerpc_decode_as_change(const char *name, gconstpointer pattern, gpointer handle, gchar* list_name)
979{
980 decode_dcerpc_bind_values_t *binding = (decode_dcerpc_bind_values_t*)pattern;
981 decode_dcerpc_bind_values_t *stored_binding;
982 guid_key *key = *((guid_key**)handle);
983
984
985 binding->ifname = g_string_new(list_name);
986 binding->uuid = key->guid;
987 binding->ver = key->ver;
988
989 /* remove a probably existing old binding */
990 decode_dcerpc_binding_reset(name, binding);
991
992 /* clone the new binding and append it to the list */
993 stored_binding = g_new(decode_dcerpc_bind_values_t,1)(decode_dcerpc_bind_values_t *) (__extension__ ({ gsize __n =
(gsize) (1); gsize __s = sizeof (decode_dcerpc_bind_values_t
); gpointer __p; if (__s == 1) __p = g_malloc (__n); else if (
__builtin_constant_p (__n) && (__s == 0 || __n <= (
9223372036854775807L *2UL+1UL) / __s)) __p = g_malloc (__n * __s
); else __p = g_malloc_n (__n, __s); __p; }));
994 *stored_binding = *binding;
995 copy_address(&stored_binding->addr_a, &binding->addr_a);
996 copy_address(&stored_binding->addr_b, &binding->addr_b);
997 stored_binding->ifname = g_string_new(binding->ifname->str);
998
999 decode_dcerpc_bindings = g_slist_append (decode_dcerpc_bindings, stored_binding);
1000
1001 return FALSE(0);
1002}

1026/* try to desegment big DCE/RPC packets over TCP? */
1027static gboolean dcerpc_cn_desegment = TRUE(!(0));
1028
1029/* reassemble DCE/RPC fragments */
1030/* reassembly of cl dcerpc fragments will not work for the case where ONE frame
1031 might contain multiple dcerpc fragments for different PDUs.
1032 this case would be so unusual/weird so if you got captures like that:
1033 too bad
1034
1035 reassembly of co dcerpc fragments will not work for the case where TCP/SMB frames
1036 are coming in out of sequence, but that will hurt in a lot of other places as well.
1037*/
1038static gboolean dcerpc_reassemble = TRUE(!(0));
1039static reassembly_table dcerpc_co_reassembly_table;
1040static reassembly_table dcerpc_cl_reassembly_table;
1041
1042typedef struct _dcerpc_fragment_key {
1043 address src;
1044 address dst;
1045 guint32 id;
1046 e_guid_t act_id;
1047} dcerpc_fragment_key;
1048
1049static guint
1050dcerpc_fragment_hash(gconstpointer k)
1051{
1052 const dcerpc_fragment_key* key = (const dcerpc_fragment_key*) k;
1053 guint hash_val;
1054
1055 hash_val = 0;
1056
1057 hash_val += key->id;
1058 hash_val += key->act_id.data1;
1059 hash_val += key->act_id.data2 << 16;
1060 hash_val += key->act_id.data3;
1061
1062 return hash_val;
1063}
1064
1065static gint
1066dcerpc_fragment_equal(gconstpointer k1, gconstpointer k2)
1067{
1068 const dcerpc_fragment_key* key1 = (const dcerpc_fragment_key*) k1;
1069 const dcerpc_fragment_key* key2 = (const dcerpc_fragment_key*) k2;
1070
1071 /*key.id is the first item to compare since item is most
1072 likely to differ between sessions, thus shortcircuiting
1073 the comparison of addresses.
1074 */
1075 return (((key1->id == key2->id)
1076 && (addresses_equal(&key1->src, &key2->src))
1077 && (addresses_equal(&key1->dst, &key2->dst))
1078 && (memcmp (&key1->act_id, &key2->act_id, sizeof (e_guid_t)) == 0))
1079 ? TRUE(!(0)) : FALSE(0));
1080}
1081
1082/* allocate a persistent dcerpc fragment key to insert in the hash */
1083static void *
1084dcerpc_fragment_temporary_key(const packet_info *pinfo, const guint32 id,
1085 const void *data)
1086{
1087 dcerpc_fragment_key *key = g_slice_new(dcerpc_fragment_key)((dcerpc_fragment_key*) g_slice_alloc (sizeof (dcerpc_fragment_key
)));
1088 const e_dce_dg_common_hdr_t *hdr = (const e_dce_dg_common_hdr_t *)data;
1089
1090 copy_address_shallow(&key->src, &pinfo->src);
1091 copy_address_shallow(&key->dst, &pinfo->dst);
1092 key->id = id;
1093 key->act_id = hdr->act_id;
1094
1095 return key;
1096}
1097
1098/* allocate a persistent dcerpc fragment key to insert in the hash */
1099static void *
1100dcerpc_fragment_persistent_key(const packet_info *pinfo, const guint32 id,
1101 const void *data)
1102{
1103 dcerpc_fragment_key *key = g_slice_new(dcerpc_fragment_key)((dcerpc_fragment_key*) g_slice_alloc (sizeof (dcerpc_fragment_key
)));
1104 const e_dce_dg_common_hdr_t *hdr = (const e_dce_dg_common_hdr_t *)data;
1105
1106 copy_address(&key->src, &pinfo->src);
1107 copy_address(&key->dst, &pinfo->dst);
1108 key->id = id;
1109 key->act_id = hdr->act_id;
1110
1111 return key;
1112}

1115dcerpc_fragment_free_temporary_key(gpointer ptr)
1116{
1117 dcerpc_fragment_key *key = (dcerpc_fragment_key *)ptr;
1118
1119 if (key)
1120 g_slice_free(dcerpc_fragment_key, key)do { if (1) g_slice_free1 (sizeof (dcerpc_fragment_key), (key
)); else (void) ((dcerpc_fragment_key*) 0 == (key)); } while (
0);
1121}
1122
1123static void
1124dcerpc_fragment_free_persistent_key(gpointer ptr)
1125{
1126 dcerpc_fragment_key *key = (dcerpc_fragment_key *)ptr;
1127
1128 if (key) {
1129 /*
1130 * Free up the copies of the addresses from the old key.
1131 */
1132 free_address(&key->src);
1133 free_address(&key->dst);
1134
1135 g_slice_free(dcerpc_fragment_key, key)do { if (1) g_slice_free1 (sizeof (dcerpc_fragment_key), (key
)); else (void) ((dcerpc_fragment_key*) 0 == (key)); } while (
0);
1136 }
1137}

1162/*
1163 * Authentication subdissectors. Used to dissect authentication blobs in
1164 * DCERPC binds, requests and responses.
1165 */
1166
1167typedef struct _dcerpc_auth_subdissector {
1168 guint8 auth_level;
1169 guint8 auth_type;
1170 dcerpc_auth_subdissector_fns auth_fns;
1171} dcerpc_auth_subdissector;
1172
1173static GSList *dcerpc_auth_subdissector_list;
1174
1175static dcerpc_auth_subdissector_fns *get_auth_subdissector_fns(
1176 guint8 auth_level, guint8 auth_type)
1177{
1178 gpointer data;
1179 int i;
1180
1181 for (i = 0; (data = g_slist_nth_data(dcerpc_auth_subdissector_list, i)); i++) {
1182 dcerpc_auth_subdissector *asd = (dcerpc_auth_subdissector *)data;
1183
1184 if ((asd->auth_level == auth_level) &&
1185 (asd->auth_type == auth_type))
1186 return &asd->auth_fns;
1187 }
1188
1189 return NULL((void*)0);
1190}
1191
1192void register_dcerpc_auth_subdissector(guint8 auth_level, guint8 auth_type,
1193 dcerpc_auth_subdissector_fns *fns)
1194{
1195 dcerpc_auth_subdissector *d;
1196
1197 if (get_auth_subdissector_fns(auth_level, auth_type))
1198 return;
1199
1200 d = (dcerpc_auth_subdissector *)g_malloc(sizeof(dcerpc_auth_subdissector));
1201
1202 d->auth_level = auth_level;
1203 d->auth_type = auth_type;
1204 memcpy(&d->auth_fns, fns, sizeof(dcerpc_auth_subdissector_fns));
1205
1206 dcerpc_auth_subdissector_list = g_slist_append(dcerpc_auth_subdissector_list, d);
1207}
1208
1209/* Hand off verifier data to a registered dissector */
1210
1211static void dissect_auth_verf(tvbuff_t *auth_tvb, packet_info *pinfo,
1212 proto_tree *tree,
1213 dcerpc_auth_subdissector_fns *auth_fns,
1214 e_dce_cn_common_hdr_t *hdr,
1215 dcerpc_auth_info *auth_info)
1216{
1217 dcerpc_dissect_fnct_t *fn = NULL((void*)0);
1218 /* XXX - "stub" a fake DCERPC INFO STRUCTURE
1219 If a dcerpc_info is really needed, update
1220 the call stacks to include it
1221 */
1222 FAKE_DCERPC_INFO_STRUCTUREdcerpc_info di; dcerpc_call_value call_data; di.conformant_run
= (0); di.no_align = (!(0)); call_data.flags = 0; di.call_data
= &call_data;
1223
1224 switch (hdr->ptype) {
1225 case PDU_BIND11:
1226 case PDU_ALTER14:
1227 fn = auth_fns->bind_fn;
1228 break;
1229 case PDU_BIND_ACK12:
1230 case PDU_ALTER_ACK15:
1231 fn = auth_fns->bind_ack_fn;
1232 break;
1233 case PDU_AUTH316:
1234 fn = auth_fns->auth3_fn;
1235 break;
1236 case PDU_REQ0:
1237 fn = auth_fns->req_verf_fn;
1238 break;
1239 case PDU_RESP2:
1240 fn = auth_fns->resp_verf_fn;
1241 break;
1242
1243 default:
1244 /* Don't know how to handle authentication data in this
1245 pdu type. */
1246 proto_tree_add_expert_format(tree, pinfo, &ei_dcerpc_invalid_pdu_authentication_attempt,
1247 auth_tvb, 0, 0,
1248 "Don't know how to dissect authentication data for %s pdu type",
1249 val_to_str(hdr->ptype, pckt_vals, "Unknown (%u)"));
1250 return;
1251 break;
1252 }
1253
1254 if (fn)
1255 fn(auth_tvb, 0, pinfo, tree, &di, hdr->drep);
1256 else {
1257 proto_tree_add_expert_format(tree, pinfo, &ei_dcerpc_verifier_unavailable,
1258 auth_tvb, 0, hdr->auth_len,
1259 "%s Verifier unavailable",
1260 val_to_str(auth_info->auth_type,
1261 authn_protocol_vals,
1262 "Unknown (%u)"));
1263 }
1264}
1265
1266static proto_item*
1267proto_tree_add_dcerpc_drep(proto_tree *tree, tvbuff_t *tvb, int offset, guint8 drep[], int drep_len)
1268{
1269 const guint8 byteorder = drep[0] >> 4;
1270 const guint8 character = drep[0] & 0x0f;
1271 const guint8 fp = drep[1];
1272 proto_item *ti = proto_tree_add_bytes(tree, hf_dcerpc_drep, tvb, offset, drep_len, drep);
1273 proto_tree *tr = proto_item_add_subtree(ti, ett_dcerpc_drep);
1274
1275 proto_tree_add_uint(tr, hf_dcerpc_drep_byteorder, tvb, offset, 1, byteorder);
1276 proto_tree_add_uint(tr, hf_dcerpc_drep_character, tvb, offset, 1, character);
1277 proto_tree_add_uint(tr, hf_dcerpc_drep_fp, tvb, offset+1, 1, fp);
1278
1279 proto_item_append_text(ti, " (Order: %s, Char: %s, Float: %s)",
1280 val_to_str(byteorder, drep_byteorder_vals, "Unknown (%u)"),
1281 val_to_str(character, drep_character_vals, "Unknown (%u)"),
1282 val_to_str(fp, drep_fp_vals, "Unknown (%u)"));
1283 return ti;
1284}
1285
1286/* Hand off payload data to a registered dissector */
1287
1288static tvbuff_t *decode_encrypted_data(tvbuff_t *data_tvb,
1289 tvbuff_t *auth_tvb,
1290 packet_info *pinfo,
1291 dcerpc_auth_subdissector_fns *auth_fns,
1292 gboolean is_request,
1293 dcerpc_auth_info *auth_info)
1294{
1295 dcerpc_decode_data_fnct_t *fn;
1296
1297 if (is_request)
1298 fn = auth_fns->req_data_fn;
1299 else
1300 fn = auth_fns->resp_data_fn;
1301
1302 if (fn)
1303 return fn(data_tvb, auth_tvb, 0, pinfo, auth_info);
1304
1305 return NULL((void*)0);
1306}

1308typedef struct _dcerpc_dissector_data
1309{
1310 dcerpc_uuid_value *sub_proto;
1311 dcerpc_info *info;
1312 gboolean decrypted;
1313 dcerpc_auth_info *auth_info;
1314 guint8 *drep;
1315 proto_tree *dcerpc_tree;
1316} dcerpc_dissector_data_t;
1317
1318/*
1319 * Subdissectors
1320 */
1321
1322dissector_table_t uuid_dissector_table;
1323
1324/* the registered subdissectors */
1325GHashTable *dcerpc_uuids = NULL((void*)0);
1326
1327static gint
1328dcerpc_uuid_equal(gconstpointer k1, gconstpointer k2)
1329{
1330 const guid_key *key1 = (const guid_key *)k1;
1331 const guid_key *key2 = (const guid_key *)k2;
1332 return ((memcmp(&key1->guid, &key2->guid, sizeof (e_guid_t)) == 0)
1333 && (key1->ver == key2->ver));
1334}
1335
1336static guint
1337dcerpc_uuid_hash(gconstpointer k)
1338{
1339 const guid_key *key = (const guid_key *)k;
1340 /* This isn't perfect, but the Data1 part of these is almost always
1341 unique. */
1342 return key->guid.data1;
1343}

1345
1346static int
1347dissect_verification_trailer(packet_info *pinfo, tvbuff_t *tvb, int stub_offset,
1348 proto_tree *parent_tree, int *signature_offset);
1349
1350static void
1351show_stub_data(packet_info *pinfo, tvbuff_t *tvb, gint offset, proto_tree *dcerpc_tree,
1352 dcerpc_auth_info *auth_info, gboolean is_encrypted)
1353{
1354 int length, plain_length, auth_pad_len;
1355 guint auth_pad_offset;
1356
1357 /*
1358 * We don't show stub data unless we have some in the tvbuff;
1359 * however, in the protocol tree, we show, as the number of
1360 * bytes, the reported number of bytes, not the number of bytes
1361 * that happen to be in the tvbuff.
1362 */
1363 if (tvb_reported_length_remaining(tvb, offset) > 0) {
1364 auth_pad_len = auth_info?auth_info->auth_pad_len:0;
1365 length = tvb_reported_length_remaining(tvb, offset);
1366
1367 /* if auth_pad_len is larger than length then we ignore auth_pad_len totally */
1368 plain_length = length - auth_pad_len;
1369 if (plain_length < 1) {
1370 plain_length = length;
1371 auth_pad_len = 0;
1372 }
1373 auth_pad_offset = offset + plain_length;
1374
1375 if ((auth_info != NULL((void*)0)) &&
1376 (auth_info->auth_level == DCE_C_AUTHN_LEVEL_PKT_PRIVACY6)) {
1377 if (is_encrypted) {
1378 proto_tree_add_item(dcerpc_tree, hf_dcerpc_encrypted_stub_data, tvb, offset, length, ENC_NA0x00000000);
1379 /* is the padding is still inside the encrypted blob, don't display it explicit */
1380 auth_pad_len = 0;
1381 } else {
1382 proto_tree_add_item(dcerpc_tree, hf_dcerpc_decrypted_stub_data, tvb, offset, plain_length, ENC_NA0x00000000);
1383 dissect_verification_trailer(pinfo, tvb, offset, dcerpc_tree, NULL((void*)0));
1384 }
1385 } else {
1386 proto_tree_add_item(dcerpc_tree, hf_dcerpc_stub_data, tvb, offset, plain_length, ENC_NA0x00000000);
1387 dissect_verification_trailer(pinfo, tvb, offset, dcerpc_tree, NULL((void*)0));
1388 }
1389 /* If there is auth padding at the end of the stub, display it */
1390 if (auth_pad_len != 0) {
1391 proto_tree_add_item(dcerpc_tree, hf_dcerpc_auth_padding, tvb, auth_pad_offset, auth_pad_len, ENC_NA0x00000000);
1392 }
1393 }
1394}
1395
1396static int
1397dissect_dcerpc_guid(tvbuff_t *tvb, packet_info *pinfo, proto_tree *tree, void *data)
1398{
1399 dcerpc_dissector_data_t* dissector_data = (dcerpc_dissector_data_t*)data;
1400 const gchar *name = NULL((void*)0);
1401 dcerpc_sub_dissector *proc;
1402 int (*volatile sub_dissect)(tvbuff_t *tvb, int offset, packet_info *pinfo, proto_tree *tree, dcerpc_info *di, guint8 *drep) = NULL((void*)0);
1403 proto_item *pi, *sub_item;
1404 proto_tree *sub_tree;
1405 volatile guint length;
1406 guint reported_length;
1407 volatile gint offset = 0;
1408 tvbuff_t *volatile stub_tvb;
1409 tvbuff_t *volatile payload_tvb = NULL((void*)0);
1410 volatile guint auth_pad_len;
1411 volatile int auth_pad_offset;
1412 const char *volatile saved_proto;
1413
1414 for (proc = dissector_data->sub_proto->procs; proc->name; proc++) {
1415 if (proc->num == dissector_data->info->call_data->opnum) {
1416 name = proc->name;
1417 break;
1418 }
1419 }
1420
1421 col_set_str(pinfo->cinfo, COL_PROTOCOL, dissector_data->sub_proto->name);
1422
1423 if (!name)
1424 col_add_fstr(pinfo->cinfo, COL_INFO, "Unknown operation %u %s",
1425 dissector_data->info->call_data->opnum,
1426 (dissector_data->info->ptype == PDU_REQ0) ? "request" : "response");
1427 else
1428 col_add_fstr(pinfo->cinfo, COL_INFO, "%s %s",
1429 name, (dissector_data->info->ptype == PDU_REQ0) ? "request" : "response");
1430
1431 sub_dissect = (dissector_data->info->ptype == PDU_REQ0) ?
1432 proc->dissect_rqst : proc->dissect_resp;
1433
1434 sub_item = proto_tree_add_item(tree, dissector_data->sub_proto->proto_id,
1435 tvb,//(decrypted_tvb != NULL)?decrypted_tvb:tvb,
1436 0, -1, ENC_NA0x00000000);
1437 sub_tree = proto_item_add_subtree(sub_item, dissector_data->sub_proto->ett);
1438 if (!name)
1439 proto_item_append_text(sub_item, ", unknown operation %u",
1440 dissector_data->info->call_data->opnum);
1441 else
1442 proto_item_append_text(sub_item, ", %s", name);
1443
1444 if (tree) {
1445 /*
1446 * Put the operation number into the tree along with
1447 * the operation's name.
1448 */
1449 if (dissector_data->sub_proto->opnum_hf != -1)
1450 proto_tree_add_uint_format(sub_tree, dissector_data->sub_proto->opnum_hf,
1451 tvb, 0, 0, dissector_data->info->call_data->opnum,
1452 "Operation: %s (%u)",
1453 name ? name : "Unknown operation",
1454 dissector_data->info->call_data->opnum);
1455 else
1456 proto_tree_add_uint_format_value(sub_tree, hf_dcerpc_op, tvb,
1457 0, 0, dissector_data->info->call_data->opnum,
1458 "%s (%u)",
1459 name ? name : "Unknown operation",
1460 dissector_data->info->call_data->opnum);
1461
1462 if ((dissector_data->info->ptype == PDU_REQ0) && (dissector_data->info->call_data->rep_frame != 0)) {
1463 pi = proto_tree_add_uint(sub_tree, hf_dcerpc_response_in,
1464 tvb, 0, 0, dissector_data->info->call_data->rep_frame);
1465 PROTO_ITEM_SET_GENERATED(pi)do { if (pi) do { if (((pi)->finfo)) (((pi)->finfo))->
flags = (((pi)->finfo))->flags | (0x00000002); } while(
0); } while(0);
1466 }
1467 if ((dissector_data->info->ptype == PDU_RESP2) && (dissector_data->info->call_data->req_frame != 0)) {
1468 pi = proto_tree_add_uint(sub_tree, hf_dcerpc_request_in,
1469 tvb, 0, 0, dissector_data->info->call_data->req_frame);
1470 PROTO_ITEM_SET_GENERATED(pi)do { if (pi) do { if (((pi)->finfo)) (((pi)->finfo))->
flags = (((pi)->finfo))->flags | (0x00000002); } while(
0); } while(0);
1471 }
1472 } /* tree */
1473
1474 if (!dissector_data->decrypted || (sub_dissect == NULL((void*)0)))
1475 {
1476 show_stub_data(pinfo, tvb, 0, sub_tree, dissector_data->auth_info, !dissector_data->decrypted);
1477 return tvb_captured_length(tvb);
1478 }
1479
1480 /* Either there was no encryption or we successfully decrypted
1481 the encrypted payload. */
1482
1483 /* We have a subdissector - call it. */
1484 saved_proto = pinfo->current_proto;
1485 pinfo->current_proto = dissector_data->sub_proto->name;
1486
1487 init_ndr_pointer_list(dissector_data->info);
1488
1489 length = tvb_captured_length(tvb);
1490 reported_length = tvb_reported_length(tvb);
1491
1492 /*
1493 * Remove the authentication padding from the stub data.
1494 */
1495 if ((dissector_data->auth_info != NULL((void*)0)) && (dissector_data->auth_info->auth_pad_len != 0)) {
1496 if (reported_length >= dissector_data->auth_info->auth_pad_len) {
1497 /*
1498 * OK, the padding length isn't so big that it
1499 * exceeds the stub length. Trim the reported
1500 * length of the tvbuff.
1501 */
1502 reported_length -= dissector_data->auth_info->auth_pad_len;
1503
1504 /*
1505 * If that exceeds the actual amount of data in
1506 * the tvbuff (which means we have at least one
1507 * byte of authentication padding in the tvbuff),
1508 * trim the actual amount.
1509 */
1510 if (length > reported_length)
1511 length = reported_length;
1512
1513 stub_tvb = tvb_new_subset(tvb, 0, length, reported_length);
1514 auth_pad_len = dissector_data->auth_info->auth_pad_len;
1515 auth_pad_offset = reported_length;
1516 } else {
1517 /*
1518 * The padding length exceeds the stub length.
1519 * Don't bother dissecting the stub, trim the padding
1520 * length to what's in the stub data, and show the
1521 * entire stub as authentication padding.
1522 */
1523 stub_tvb = NULL((void*)0);
1524 auth_pad_len = reported_length;
1525 auth_pad_offset = 0;
1526 length = 0;
1527 }
1528 } else {
1529 /*
1530 * No authentication padding.
1531 */
1532 stub_tvb = tvb;
1533 auth_pad_len = 0;
1534 auth_pad_offset = 0;
1535 }
1536
1537 if (sub_item) {
1538 proto_item_set_len(sub_item, length);
1539 }
1540
1541 if (stub_tvb != NULL((void*)0)) {
1542 /*
1543 * Catch all exceptions other than BoundsError, so that even
1544 * if the stub data is bad, we still show the authentication
1545 * padding, if any.
1546 *
1547 * If we get BoundsError, it means the frame was cut short
1548 * by a snapshot length, so there's nothing more to
1549 * dissect; just re-throw that exception.
1550 */
1551 TRY{ except_t *volatile exc; volatile int except_state = 0; static
const except_id_t catch_spec[] = { { 1, 0 } }; { struct except_stacknode
except_sn; struct except_catch except_ch; except_setup_try(&
except_sn, &except_ch, catch_spec, 1); if (_setjmp (except_ch
.except_jmp)) *(&exc) = &except_ch.except_obj; else *
(&exc) = 0; if(except_state & 1) except_state |= 2; except_state
&= ~1; if (except_state == 0 && exc == 0) {
1552 proto_tree *stub_tree = NULL((void*)0);
1553 int remaining;
1554 int trailer_start_offset = -1;
1555 int trailer_end_offset = -1;
1556
1557 stub_tree = proto_tree_add_subtree_format(dissector_data->dcerpc_tree,
1558 stub_tvb, 0, length,
1559 ett_dcerpc_complete_stub_data, NULL((void*)0),
1560 "Complete stub data (%d byte%s)", length,
1561 plurality(length, "", "s")((length) == 1 ? ("") : ("s")));
1562 trailer_end_offset = dissect_verification_trailer(pinfo,
1563 stub_tvb, 0,
1564 stub_tree,
1565 &trailer_start_offset);
1566
1567 if (trailer_end_offset != -1) {
1568 remaining = tvb_captured_length_remaining(stub_tvb,
1569 trailer_start_offset);
1570 length -= remaining;
1571
1572 if (sub_item) {
1573 proto_item_set_len(sub_item, length);
1574 }
1575 } else {
1576 proto_item *payload_item;
1577
1578 payload_item = proto_tree_add_item(stub_tree,
1579 hf_dcerpc_payload_stub_data,
1580 stub_tvb, 0, length, ENC_NA0x00000000);
1581 proto_item_append_text(payload_item, " (%d byte%s)",
1582 length, plurality(length, "", "s")((length) == 1 ? ("") : ("s")));
1583 }
1584
1585 payload_tvb = tvb_new_subset(stub_tvb, 0, length, length);
1586 offset = sub_dissect(payload_tvb, 0, pinfo, sub_tree,
1587 dissector_data->info, dissector_data->drep);
1588
1589 /* If we have a subdissector and it didn't dissect all
1590 data in the tvb, make a note of it. */
1591 remaining = tvb_reported_length_remaining(stub_tvb, offset);
1592
1593 if (trailer_end_offset != -1) {
1594 if (offset > trailer_start_offset) {
1595 remaining = offset - trailer_start_offset;
1596 proto_tree_add_item(sub_tree, hf_dcerpc_stub_data_with_sec_vt,
1597 stub_tvb, trailer_start_offset, remaining, ENC_NA0x00000000);
1598 col_append_fstr(pinfo->cinfo, COL_INFO,
1599 "[Payload with Verification Trailer (%d byte%s)]",
1600 remaining,
1601 plurality(remaining, "", "s")((remaining) == 1 ? ("") : ("s")));
1602 remaining = 0;
1603 } else {
1604 remaining = trailer_start_offset - offset;
1605 }
1606 }
1607
1608 if (remaining > 0) {
1609 proto_tree_add_expert(sub_tree, pinfo, &ei_dcerpc_long_frame, stub_tvb, offset, remaining);
1610 col_append_fstr(pinfo->cinfo, COL_INFO,
1611 "[Long frame (%d byte%s)]",
1612 remaining,
1613 plurality(remaining, "", "s")((remaining) == 1 ? ("") : ("s")));
1614 }
1615 } CATCH_NONFATAL_ERRORSif (except_state == 0 && exc != 0 && (exc->
except_id.except_code == (2) || exc->except_id.except_code
== (6) || exc->except_id.except_code == (8)) && (
except_state|=1)) {
1616 /*
1617 * Somebody threw an exception that means that there
1618 * was a problem dissecting the payload; that means
1619 * that a dissector was found, so we don't need to
1620 * dissect the payload as data or update the protocol
1621 * or info columns.
1622 *
1623 * Just show the exception and then drive on to show
1624 * the authentication padding.
1625 */
1626 show_exception(stub_tvb, pinfo, tree, EXCEPT_CODE((exc)->except_id.except_code), GET_MESSAGE((exc)->except_message));
1627 } ENDTRYif(!(except_state&1) && exc != 0) except_rethrow(
exc); except_free(except_ch.except_obj.except_dyndata); except_pop
(); };};
1628 }
1629
1630 /* If there is auth padding at the end of the stub, display it */
1631 if (auth_pad_len != 0) {
1632 proto_tree_add_item(sub_tree, hf_dcerpc_auth_padding, tvb, auth_pad_offset, auth_pad_len, ENC_NA0x00000000);
1633 }
1634
1635 pinfo->current_proto = saved_proto;
1636
1637 return tvb_captured_length(tvb);
1638}

1640void
1641dcerpc_init_uuid(int proto, int ett, e_guid_t *uuid, guint16 ver,
1642 dcerpc_sub_dissector *procs, int opnum_hf)
1643{
1644 guid_key *key = (guid_key *)g_malloc(sizeof (*key));
1645 dcerpc_uuid_value *value = (dcerpc_uuid_value *)g_malloc(sizeof (*value));
1646 header_field_info *hf_info;
1647 module_t *samr_module;
1648 const char *filter_name = proto_get_protocol_filter_name(proto);
1649 dissector_handle_t guid_handle;
1650
1651 key->guid = *uuid;
1652 key->ver = ver;
1653
1654 value->proto = find_protocol_by_id(proto);
1655 value->proto_id = proto;
1656 value->ett = ett;
1657 value->name = proto_get_protocol_short_name(value->proto);
1658 value->procs = procs;
1659 value->opnum_hf = opnum_hf;
1660
1661 g_hash_table_insert(dcerpc_uuids, key, value);
1662
1663 hf_info = proto_registrar_get_nth(opnum_hf);
1664 hf_info->strings = value_string_from_subdissectors(procs);
1665
1666 /* Register the GUID with the dissector table */
1667 guid_handle = create_dissector_handle( dissect_dcerpc_guid, proto);
1668 dissector_add_guid( "dcerpc.uuid", key, guid_handle );
1669
1670 /* add this GUID to the global name resolving */
1671 guids_add_uuid(uuid, proto_get_protocol_short_name(value->proto))guids_add_guid((const e_guid_t *) (uuid), (proto_get_protocol_short_name
(value->proto)));
1672
1673 /* Register the samr.nt_password preference as obsolete */
1674 /* This should be in packet-dcerpc-samr.c */
1675 if (strcmp(filter_name, "samr") == 0) {
1676 samr_module = prefs_register_protocol(proto, NULL((void*)0));
1677 prefs_register_obsolete_preference(samr_module, "nt_password");
1678 }
1679}

1681/* Function to find the name of a registered protocol
1682 * or NULL if the protocol/version is not known to wireshark.
1683 */
1684const char *
1685dcerpc_get_proto_name(e_guid_t *uuid, guint16 ver)
1686{
1687 dissector_handle_t handle;
1688 guid_key key;
1689
1690 key.guid = *uuid;
1691 key.ver = ver;
1692
1693 handle = dissector_get_guid_handle(uuid_dissector_table, &key);
1694 if (handle == NULL((void*)0)) {
1695 return NULL((void*)0);
1696 }
1697
1698 return dissector_handle_get_short_name(handle);
1699}
1700
1701/* Function to find the opnum hf-field of a registered protocol
1702 * or -1 if the protocol/version is not known to wireshark.
1703 */
1704int
1705dcerpc_get_proto_hf_opnum(e_guid_t *uuid, guint16 ver)
1706{
1707 guid_key key;
1708 dcerpc_uuid_value *sub_proto;
1709
1710 key.guid = *uuid;
1711 key.ver = ver;
1712 if (!(sub_proto = (dcerpc_uuid_value *)g_hash_table_lookup(dcerpc_uuids, &key))) {
1713 return -1;
1714 }
1715 return sub_proto->opnum_hf;
1716}
1717
1718/* Create a value_string consisting of DCERPC opnum and name from a
1719 subdissector array. */
1720
1721value_string *value_string_from_subdissectors(dcerpc_sub_dissector *sd)
1722{
1723 value_string *vs = NULL((void*)0);
1724 int i;
1725 int num_sd = 0;
1726
1727again:
1728 for (i = 0; sd[i].name; i++) {
1729 if (vs) {
1730 vs[i].value = sd[i].num;
1731 vs[i].strptr = sd[i].name;
1732 } else
1733 num_sd++;
1734 }
1735
1736 if (!vs) {
1737 vs = (value_string *)wmem_alloc(wmem_epan_scope(), (num_sd + 1) * sizeof(value_string));
1738 goto again;
1739 }
1740
1741 vs[num_sd].value = 0;
1742 vs[num_sd].strptr = NULL((void*)0);
1743
1744 return vs;
1745}
1746
1747/* Function to find the subdissector table of a registered protocol
1748 * or NULL if the protocol/version is not known to wireshark.
1749 */
1750dcerpc_sub_dissector *
1751dcerpc_get_proto_sub_dissector(e_guid_t *uuid, guint16 ver)
1752{
1753 guid_key key;
1754 dcerpc_uuid_value *sub_proto;
1755
1756 key.guid = *uuid;
1757 key.ver = ver;
1758 if (!(sub_proto = (dcerpc_uuid_value *)g_hash_table_lookup(dcerpc_uuids, &key))) {
1759 return NULL((void*)0);
1760 }
1761 return sub_proto->procs;
1762}

1766static gint
1767dcerpc_bind_equal(gconstpointer k1, gconstpointer k2)
1768{
1769 const dcerpc_bind_key *key1 = (const dcerpc_bind_key *)k1;
1770 const dcerpc_bind_key *key2 = (const dcerpc_bind_key *)k2;
1771 return ((key1->conv == key2->conv)
1772 && (key1->ctx_id == key2->ctx_id)
1773 && (key1->transport_salt == key2->transport_salt));
1774}
1775
1776static guint
1777dcerpc_bind_hash(gconstpointer k)
1778{
1779 const dcerpc_bind_key *key = (const dcerpc_bind_key *)k;
1780 guint hash;
1781
1782 hash = GPOINTER_TO_UINT(key->conv)((guint) (gulong) (key->conv));
1783 hash += key->ctx_id;
1784 /* sizeof(guint) might be smaller than sizeof(guint64) */
1785 hash += (guint)key->transport_salt;
1786 hash += (guint)(key->transport_salt << sizeof(guint));
1787
1788 return hash;
1789}

1791/*
1792 * To keep track of callid mappings. Should really use some generic
1793 * conversation support instead.
1794 */
1795static GHashTable *dcerpc_cn_calls = NULL((void*)0);
1796static GHashTable *dcerpc_dg_calls = NULL((void*)0);
1797
1798typedef struct _dcerpc_cn_call_key {
1799 conversation_t *conv;
1800 guint32 call_id;
1801 guint64 transport_salt;
1802} dcerpc_cn_call_key;
1803
1804typedef struct _dcerpc_dg_call_key {
1805 conversation_t *conv;
1806 guint32 seqnum;
1807 e_guid_t act_id ;
1808} dcerpc_dg_call_key;
1809
1810
1811static gint
1812dcerpc_cn_call_equal(gconstpointer k1, gconstpointer k2)
1813{
1814 const dcerpc_cn_call_key *key1 = (const dcerpc_cn_call_key *)k1;
1815 const dcerpc_cn_call_key *key2 = (const dcerpc_cn_call_key *)k2;
1816 return ((key1->conv == key2->conv)
1817 && (key1->call_id == key2->call_id)
1818 && (key1->transport_salt == key2->transport_salt));
1819}
1820
1821static gint
1822dcerpc_dg_call_equal(gconstpointer k1, gconstpointer k2)
1823{
1824 const dcerpc_dg_call_key *key1 = (const dcerpc_dg_call_key *)k1;
1825 const dcerpc_dg_call_key *key2 = (const dcerpc_dg_call_key *)k2;
1826 return ((key1->conv == key2->conv)
1827 && (key1->seqnum == key2->seqnum)
1828 && ((memcmp(&key1->act_id, &key2->act_id, sizeof (e_guid_t)) == 0)));
1829}
1830
1831static guint
1832dcerpc_cn_call_hash(gconstpointer k)
1833{
1834 const dcerpc_cn_call_key *key = (const dcerpc_cn_call_key *)k;
1835 guint hash;
1836
1837 hash = GPOINTER_TO_UINT(key->conv)((guint) (gulong) (key->conv));
1838 hash += key->call_id;
1839 /* sizeof(guint) might be smaller than sizeof(guint64) */
1840 hash += (guint)key->transport_salt;
1841 hash += (guint)(key->transport_salt << sizeof(guint));
1842
1843 return hash;
1844}
1845
1846static guint
1847dcerpc_dg_call_hash(gconstpointer k)
1848{
1849 const dcerpc_dg_call_key *key = (const dcerpc_dg_call_key *)k;
1850 return (GPOINTER_TO_UINT(key->conv)((guint) (gulong) (key->conv)) + key->seqnum + key->act_id.data1
1851 + (key->act_id.data2 << 16) + key->act_id.data3
1852 + (key->act_id.data4[0] << 24) + (key->act_id.data4[1] << 16)
1853 + (key->act_id.data4[2] << 8) + (key->act_id.data4[3] << 0)
1854 + (key->act_id.data4[4] << 24) + (key->act_id.data4[5] << 16)
1855 + (key->act_id.data4[6] << 8) + (key->act_id.data4[7] << 0));
1856}

1858/* to keep track of matched calls/responses
1859 this one uses the same value struct as calls, but the key is the frame id
1860 and call id; there can be more than one call in a frame.
1861
1862 XXX - why not just use the same keys as are used for calls?
1863*/
1864
1865static GHashTable *dcerpc_matched = NULL((void*)0);
1866
1867typedef struct _dcerpc_matched_key {
1868 guint32 frame;
1869 guint32 call_id;
1870} dcerpc_matched_key;
1871
1872static gint
1873dcerpc_matched_equal(gconstpointer k1, gconstpointer k2)
1874{
1875 const dcerpc_matched_key *key1 = (const dcerpc_matched_key *)k1;
1876 const dcerpc_matched_key *key2 = (const dcerpc_matched_key *)k2;
1877 return ((key1->frame == key2->frame)
1878 && (key1->call_id == key2->call_id));
1879}
1880
1881static guint
1882dcerpc_matched_hash(gconstpointer k)
1883{
1884 const dcerpc_matched_key *key = (const dcerpc_matched_key *)k;
1885 return key->frame;
1886}

1888static gboolean
1889uuid_equal(e_guid_t *uuid1, e_guid_t *uuid2)
1890{
1891 if( (uuid1->data1 != uuid2->data1)
1892 ||(uuid1->data2 != uuid2->data2)
1893 ||(uuid1->data3 != uuid2->data3)
1894 ||(uuid1->data4[0] != uuid2->data4[0])
1895 ||(uuid1->data4[1] != uuid2->data4[1])
1896 ||(uuid1->data4[2] != uuid2->data4[2])
1897 ||(uuid1->data4[3] != uuid2->data4[3])
1898 ||(uuid1->data4[4] != uuid2->data4[4])
1899 ||(uuid1->data4[5] != uuid2->data4[5])
1900 ||(uuid1->data4[6] != uuid2->data4[6])
1901 ||(uuid1->data4[7] != uuid2->data4[7]) ){
1902 return FALSE(0);
1903 }
1904 return TRUE(!(0));
1905}

1909{

1911 srt_stat_table *dcerpc_srt_table;

1913 dcerpc_sub_dissector *procs;
1914
1915 DISSECTOR_ASSERT(tap_data)((void) ((tap_data) ? (void)0 : (proto_report_dissector_bug(wmem_strdup_printf
(wmem_packet_scope(), "%s:%u: failed assertion \"%s\"", "/home/remnux/Desktop/Thesis-Experiments/Third_Experiment/SAST_With_SRE/CVEs/CVE-2018-11360_Wireshark/Wireshark/epan/dissectors/packet-dcerpc.c"
, 1915, "tap_data")))));

1922 } else {
1923 dcerpc_srt_table = init_srt_table(tap_data->prog, NULL((void*)0), srt_array, tap_data->num_procedures, NULL((void*)0), NULL((void*)0), gui_callback, gui_data, tap_data);
1924 }

1931 for(j=0;procs[j].name;j++)
1932 {
1933 if (procs[j].num == i)

1935 proc_name = procs[j].name;

1942
1943static int
1944dcerpcstat_packet(void *pss, packet_info *pinfo, epan_dissect_t *edt _U___attribute__((unused)), const void *prv)
1945{
1946 guint i = 0;
1947 srt_stat_table *dcerpc_srt_table;
1948 srt_data_t *data = (srt_data_t *)pss;
1949 const dcerpc_info *ri = (const dcerpc_info *)prv;
1950 dcerpcstat_tap_data_t* tap_data;
1951
1952 dcerpc_srt_table = g_array_index(data->srt_array, srt_stat_table*, i)(((srt_stat_table**) (void *) (data->srt_array)->data) [
(i)]);
1953 tap_data = (dcerpcstat_tap_data_t*)dcerpc_srt_table->table_specific_data;
1954
1955 if(!ri->call_data){
1956 return 0;
1957 }
1958 if(!ri->call_data->req_frame){
1959 /* we have not seen the request so we don't know the delta*/
1960 return 0;
1961 }
1962 if(ri->call_data->opnum >= tap_data->num_procedures){
1963 /* don't handle this since it's outside of known table */
1964 return 0;
1965 }
1966
1967 /* we are only interested in reply packets */
1968 if(ri->ptype != PDU_RESP2){
1969 return 0;
1970 }
1971
1972 /* we are only interested in certain program/versions */
1973 if( (!uuid_equal( (&ri->call_data->uuid), (&tap_data->uuid)))
1974 ||(ri->call_data->ver != tap_data->ver)){
1975 return 0;
1976 }
1977
1978 add_srt_table_data(dcerpc_srt_table, ri->call_data->opnum, &ri->call_data->req_time, pinfo);
1979
1980 return 1;
1981}
1982
1983static guint
1984dcerpcstat_param(register_srt_t* srt, const char* opt_arg, char** err)
1985{
1986 int pos = 0;
1987 guint32 i, max_procs;
1988 dcerpcstat_tap_data_t* tap_data;
1989 guint d1,d2,d3,d40,d41,d42,d43,d44,d45,d46,d47;
1990 int major, minor;
1991 guint16 ver;
1992 dcerpc_sub_dissector *procs;
1993
1994 if (sscanf(opt_arg, ",%08x-%04x-%04x-%02x%02x-%02x%02x%02x%02x%02x%02x,%d.%d%n",
1995 &d1,&d2,&d3,&d40,&d41,&d42,&d43,&d44,&d45,&d46,&d47,&major,&minor,&pos) == 13)
1996 {
1997 if ((major < 0) || (major > 65535)) {
1998 *err = g_strdup_printf("dcerpcstat_init() Major version number %d is invalid - must be positive and <= 65535", major);
1999 return pos;
2000 }
2001 if ((minor < 0) || (minor > 65535)) {
2002 *err = g_strdup_printf("dcerpcstat_init() Minor version number %d is invalid - must be positive and <= 65535", minor);
2003 return pos;
2004 }
2005 ver = major;
2006
2007 tap_data = g_new0(dcerpcstat_tap_data_t, 1)(dcerpcstat_tap_data_t *) (__extension__ ({ gsize __n = (gsize
) (1); gsize __s = sizeof (dcerpcstat_tap_data_t); gpointer __p
; if (__s == 1) __p = g_malloc0 (__n); else if (__builtin_constant_p
(__n) && (__s == 0 || __n <= (9223372036854775807L
*2UL+1UL) / __s)) __p = g_malloc0 (__n * __s); else __p = g_malloc0_n
(__n, __s); __p; }));
2008
2009 tap_data->uuid.data1 = d1;
2010 tap_data->uuid.data2 = d2;
2011 tap_data->uuid.data3 = d3;
2012 tap_data->uuid.data4[0] = d40;
2013 tap_data->uuid.data4[1] = d41;
2014 tap_data->uuid.data4[2] = d42;
2015 tap_data->uuid.data4[3] = d43;
2016 tap_data->uuid.data4[4] = d44;
2017 tap_data->uuid.data4[5] = d45;
2018 tap_data->uuid.data4[6] = d46;
2019 tap_data->uuid.data4[7] = d47;
2020
2021 procs = dcerpc_get_proto_sub_dissector(&tap_data->uuid, ver);
2022 tap_data->prog = dcerpc_get_proto_name(&tap_data->uuid, ver);
2023 tap_data->ver = ver;
2024
2025 for(i=0,max_procs=0;procs[i].name;i++)
2026 {
2027 if(procs[i].num>max_procs)
2028 {
2029 max_procs = procs[i].num;
2030 }
2031 }
2032 tap_data->num_procedures = max_procs+1;
2033
2034 set_srt_table_param_data(srt, tap_data);
2035 }
2036 else
2037 {
2038 *err = g_strdup_printf("<uuid>,<major version>.<minor version>[,<filter>]");
2039 }
2040
2041 return pos;
2042}

2049int
2050dissect_dcerpc_uint8(tvbuff_t *tvb, gint offset, packet_info *pinfo _U___attribute__((unused)),
2051 proto_tree *tree, guint8 *drep,
2052 int hfindex, guint8 *pdata)
2053{
2054 guint8 data;
2055
2056 data = tvb_get_guint8(tvb, offset);
2057 if (hfindex != -1) {
2058 proto_tree_add_item(tree, hfindex, tvb, offset, 1, DREP_ENC_INTEGER(drep)(((drep)[0] & 0x10) ? 0x80000000 : 0x00000000));
2059 }
2060 if (pdata)
2061 *pdata = data;
2062 tvb_ensure_bytes_exist(tvb, offset, 1);
2063 return offset + 1;
2064}

2079 }

2082 tvb_ensure_bytes_exist(tvb, offset, 2);

2108dissect_dcerpc_time_t(tvbuff_t *tvb, gint offset, packet_info *pinfo _U___attribute__((unused)),
2109 proto_tree *tree, guint8 *drep,
2110 int hfindex, guint32 *pdata)
2111{
2112 guint32 data;
2113 nstime_t tv;
2114
2115 data = ((drep[0] & DREP_LITTLE_ENDIAN0x10)
2116 ? tvb_get_letohl(tvb, offset)
2117 : tvb_get_ntohl(tvb, offset));

2119 tv.secs = data;
2120 tv.nsecs = 0;
2121 if (hfindex != -1) {
2122 if (data == 0xffffffff) {
2123 /* special case, no time specified */
2124 proto_tree_add_time_format_value(tree, hfindex, tvb, offset, 4, &tv, "No time specified");
2125 } else {
2126 proto_tree_add_time(tree, hfindex, tvb, offset, 4, &tv);
2127 }
2128 }

2130 *pdata = data;

2133 return offset+4;

2136int
2137dissect_dcerpc_uint64(tvbuff_t *tvb, gint offset, packet_info *pinfo _U___attribute__((unused)),
2138 proto_tree *tree, dcerpc_info *di, guint8 *drep,
2139 int hfindex, guint64 *pdata)
2140{
2141 guint64 data;
2142
2143 data = ((drep[0] & DREP_LITTLE_ENDIAN0x10)
2144 ? tvb_get_letoh64(tvb, offset)
2145 : tvb_get_ntoh64(tvb, offset));
2146
2147 if (hfindex != -1) {
2148 header_field_info *hfinfo;
2149
2150 /* This might be a field that is either 32bit, in NDR or
2151 64 bits in NDR64. So we must be careful and call the right
2152 helper here
2153 */
2154 hfinfo = proto_registrar_get_nth(hfindex);
2155
2156 switch (hfinfo->type) {
2157 case FT_UINT64:
2158 proto_tree_add_uint64(tree, hfindex, tvb, offset, 8, data);
2159 break;
2160 case FT_INT64:
2161 proto_tree_add_int64(tree, hfindex, tvb, offset, 8, data);
2162 break;
2163 default:
2164 /* The value is truncated to 32bits. 64bit values have only been
2165 seen on fuzz-tested files */
2166 DISSECTOR_ASSERT((di->call_data->flags & DCERPC_IS_NDR64) || (data <= G_MAXUINT32))((void) (((di->call_data->flags & 0x00000001) || (data
<= ((guint32) 0xffffffff))) ? (void)0 : (proto_report_dissector_bug
(wmem_strdup_printf(wmem_packet_scope(), "%s:%u: failed assertion \"%s\""
, "/home/remnux/Desktop/Thesis-Experiments/Third_Experiment/SAST_With_SRE/CVEs/CVE-2018-11360_Wireshark/Wireshark/epan/dissectors/packet-dcerpc.c"
, 2166, "(di->call_data->flags & 0x00000001) || (data <= ((guint32) 0xffffffff))"
)))));
2167 proto_tree_add_uint(tree, hfindex, tvb, offset, 8, (guint32)data);
2168 }
2169 }
2170 if (pdata)
2171 *pdata = data;
2172 tvb_ensure_bytes_exist(tvb, offset, 8);
2173 return offset+8;
2174}

2177int
2178dissect_dcerpc_float(tvbuff_t *tvb, gint offset, packet_info *pinfo _U___attribute__((unused)),
2179 proto_tree *tree, guint8 *drep,
2180 int hfindex, gfloat *pdata)
2181{
2182 gfloat data;
2183
2184
2185 switch (drep[1]) {
2186 case(DCE_RPC_DREP_FP_IEEE0):
2187 data = ((drep[0] & DREP_LITTLE_ENDIAN0x10)
2188 ? tvb_get_letohieee_float(tvb, offset)
2189 : tvb_get_ntohieee_float(tvb, offset));
2190 if (tree && hfindex != -1) {
2191 proto_tree_add_float(tree, hfindex, tvb, offset, 4, data);
2192 }
2193 break;
2194 case(DCE_RPC_DREP_FP_VAX1): /* (fall trough) */
2195 case(DCE_RPC_DREP_FP_CRAY2): /* (fall trough) */
2196 case(DCE_RPC_DREP_FP_IBM3): /* (fall trough) */
2197 default:
2198 /* ToBeDone: non IEEE floating formats */
2199 /* Set data to a negative infinity value */
2200 data = -G_MAXFLOAT3.40282347e+38F;
2201 if (tree && hfindex != -1) {
2202 proto_tree_add_debug_text(tree, "DCE RPC: dissection of non IEEE floating formats currently not implemented (drep=%u)!", drep[1]);
2203 }
2204 }
2205 if (pdata)
2206 *pdata = data;
2207 tvb_ensure_bytes_exist(tvb, offset, 4);
2208 return offset + 4;
2209}

2304/* NDR arrays */
2305/* function to dissect a unidimensional conformant array */
2306static int
2307dissect_ndr_ucarray_core(tvbuff_t *tvb, gint offset, packet_info *pinfo,
2308 proto_tree *tree, dcerpc_info *di, guint8 *drep,
2309 dcerpc_dissect_fnct_t *fnct_bytes,
2310 dcerpc_dissect_fnct_blk_t *fnct_block)
2311{
2312 guint32 i;
2313 int old_offset;
2314 int conformance_size = 4;
2315
2316 /* ensure that just one pointer is set in the call */
2317 DISSECTOR_ASSERT((fnct_bytes && !fnct_block) || (!fnct_bytes && fnct_block))((void) (((fnct_bytes && !fnct_block) || (!fnct_bytes
&& fnct_block)) ? (void)0 : (proto_report_dissector_bug
(wmem_strdup_printf(wmem_packet_scope(), "%s:%u: failed assertion \"%s\""
, "/home/remnux/Desktop/Thesis-Experiments/Third_Experiment/SAST_With_SRE/CVEs/CVE-2018-11360_Wireshark/Wireshark/epan/dissectors/packet-dcerpc.c"
, 2317, "(fnct_bytes && !fnct_block) || (!fnct_bytes && fnct_block)"
)))));
2318
2319 if (di->call_data->flags & DCERPC_IS_NDR640x00000001) {
2320 conformance_size = 8;
2321 }
2322
2323 if (di->conformant_run) {
2324 guint64 val;
2325
2326 /* conformant run, just dissect the max_count header */
2327 old_offset = offset;
2328 di->conformant_run = 0;
2329 offset = dissect_ndr_uint3264(tvb, offset, pinfo, tree, di, drep,
2330 hf_dcerpc_array_max_count, &val);
2331 di->array_max_count = (gint32)val;
2332 di->array_max_count_offset = offset-conformance_size;
2333 di->conformant_run = 1;
2334 di->conformant_eaten = offset-old_offset;
2335 } else {
2336 /* we don't remember where in the bytestream this field was */
2337 proto_tree_add_uint(tree, hf_dcerpc_array_max_count, tvb, di->array_max_count_offset, conformance_size, di->array_max_count);
2338
2339 /* real run, dissect the elements */
2340 if (fnct_block) {
2341 offset = (*fnct_block)(tvb, offset, di->array_max_count,
2342 pinfo, tree, di, drep);
2343 } else {
2344 for (i=0 ;i<di->array_max_count; i++) {
2345 offset = (*fnct_bytes)(tvb, offset, pinfo, tree, di, drep);
2346 }
2347 }
2348 }
2349
2350 return offset;
2351}

2369/* function to dissect a unidimensional conformant and varying array
2370 * depending on the dissection function passed as a parameter,
2371 * content of the array will be dissected as a block or byte by byte
2372 */
2373static int
2374dissect_ndr_ucvarray_core(tvbuff_t *tvb, gint offset, packet_info *pinfo,
2375 proto_tree *tree, dcerpc_info *di, guint8 *drep,
2376 dcerpc_dissect_fnct_t *fnct_bytes,
2377 dcerpc_dissect_fnct_blk_t *fnct_block)
2378{
2379 guint32 i;
2380 int old_offset;
2381 int conformance_size = 4;
2382
2383 if (di->call_data->flags & DCERPC_IS_NDR640x00000001) {
2384 conformance_size = 8;
2385 }
2386
2387 if (di->conformant_run) {
2388 guint64 val;
2389
2390 /* conformant run, just dissect the max_count header */
2391 old_offset = offset;
2392 di->conformant_run = 0;
2393 offset = dissect_ndr_uint3264(tvb, offset, pinfo, tree, di, drep,
2394 hf_dcerpc_array_max_count, &val);
2395 DISSECTOR_ASSERT(val <= G_MAXUINT32)((void) ((val <= ((guint32) 0xffffffff)) ? (void)0 : (proto_report_dissector_bug
(wmem_strdup_printf(wmem_packet_scope(), "%s:%u: failed assertion \"%s\""
, "/home/remnux/Desktop/Thesis-Experiments/Third_Experiment/SAST_With_SRE/CVEs/CVE-2018-11360_Wireshark/Wireshark/epan/dissectors/packet-dcerpc.c"
, 2395, "val <= ((guint32) 0xffffffff)")))));
2396 di->array_max_count = (guint32)val;
2397 di->array_max_count_offset = offset-conformance_size;
2398 offset = dissect_ndr_uint3264(tvb, offset, pinfo, tree, di, drep,
2399 hf_dcerpc_array_offset, &val);
2400 DISSECTOR_ASSERT(val <= G_MAXUINT32)((void) ((val <= ((guint32) 0xffffffff)) ? (void)0 : (proto_report_dissector_bug
(wmem_strdup_printf(wmem_packet_scope(), "%s:%u: failed assertion \"%s\""
, "/home/remnux/Desktop/Thesis-Experiments/Third_Experiment/SAST_With_SRE/CVEs/CVE-2018-11360_Wireshark/Wireshark/epan/dissectors/packet-dcerpc.c"
, 2400, "val <= ((guint32) 0xffffffff)")))));
2401 di->array_offset = (guint32)val;
2402 di->array_offset_offset = offset-conformance_size;
2403 offset = dissect_ndr_uint3264(tvb, offset, pinfo, tree, di, drep,
2404 hf_dcerpc_array_actual_count, &val);
2405 DISSECTOR_ASSERT(val <= G_MAXUINT32)((void) ((val <= ((guint32) 0xffffffff)) ? (void)0 : (proto_report_dissector_bug
(wmem_strdup_printf(wmem_packet_scope(), "%s:%u: failed assertion \"%s\""
, "/home/remnux/Desktop/Thesis-Experiments/Third_Experiment/SAST_With_SRE/CVEs/CVE-2018-11360_Wireshark/Wireshark/epan/dissectors/packet-dcerpc.c"
, 2405, "val <= ((guint32) 0xffffffff)")))));
2406 di->array_actual_count = (guint32)val;
2407 di->array_actual_count_offset = offset-conformance_size;
2408 di->conformant_run = 1;
2409 di->conformant_eaten = offset-old_offset;
2410 } else {
2411 /* we don't remember where in the bytestream these fields were */
2412 proto_tree_add_uint(tree, hf_dcerpc_array_max_count, tvb, di->array_max_count_offset, conformance_size, di->array_max_count);
2413 proto_tree_add_uint(tree, hf_dcerpc_array_offset, tvb, di->array_offset_offset, conformance_size, di->array_offset);
2414 proto_tree_add_uint(tree, hf_dcerpc_array_actual_count, tvb, di->array_actual_count_offset, conformance_size, di->array_actual_count);
2415
2416 /* real run, dissect the elements */
2417 if (fnct_block) {
2418 offset = (*fnct_block)(tvb, offset, di->array_actual_count,
2419 pinfo, tree, di, drep);
2420 } else if (fnct_bytes) {
2421 for (i=0 ;i<di->array_actual_count; i++) {
2422 old_offset = offset;
2423 offset = (*fnct_bytes)(tvb, offset, pinfo, tree, di, drep);
2424 /* Make sure we're moving forward */
2425 if (old_offset >= offset)
2426 break;
2427 }
2428 }
2429 }
2430
2431 return offset;
2432}

2467 old_offset = offset;
2468 di->conformant_run = 0;
2469 offset = dissect_ndr_uint3264(tvb, offset, pinfo, tree, di, drep,
2470 hf_dcerpc_array_offset, &val);
2471 DISSECTOR_ASSERT(val <= G_MAXUINT32)((void) ((val <= ((guint32) 0xffffffff)) ? (void)0 : (proto_report_dissector_bug
(wmem_strdup_printf(wmem_packet_scope(), "%s:%u: failed assertion \"%s\""
, "/home/remnux/Desktop/Thesis-Experiments/Third_Experiment/SAST_With_SRE/CVEs/CVE-2018-11360_Wireshark/Wireshark/epan/dissectors/packet-dcerpc.c"
, 2471, "val <= ((guint32) 0xffffffff)")))));
2472 di->array_offset = (guint32)val;
2473 di->array_offset_offset = offset-conformance_size;
2474 offset = dissect_ndr_uint3264(tvb, offset, pinfo, tree, di, drep,
2475 hf_dcerpc_array_actual_count, &val);
2476 DISSECTOR_ASSERT(val <= G_MAXUINT32)((void) ((val <= ((guint32) 0xffffffff)) ? (void)0 : (proto_report_dissector_bug
(wmem_strdup_printf(wmem_packet_scope(), "%s:%u: failed assertion \"%s\""
, "/home/remnux/Desktop/Thesis-Experiments/Third_Experiment/SAST_With_SRE/CVEs/CVE-2018-11360_Wireshark/Wireshark/epan/dissectors/packet-dcerpc.c"
, 2476, "val <= ((guint32) 0xffffffff)")))));
2477 di->array_actual_count = (guint32)val;
2478 di->array_actual_count_offset = offset-conformance_size;
2479 di->conformant_run = 1;
2480 di->conformant_eaten = offset-old_offset;
2481 } else {
2482 /* we don't remember where in the bytestream these fields were */
2483 proto_tree_add_uint(tree, hf_dcerpc_array_offset, tvb, di->array_offset_offset, conformance_size, di->array_offset);
2484 proto_tree_add_uint(tree, hf_dcerpc_array_actual_count, tvb, di->array_actual_count_offset, conformance_size, di->array_actual_count);
2485
2486 /* real run, dissect the elements */
2487 for (i=0; i<di->array_actual_count; i++) {
2488 offset = (*fnct)(tvb, offset, pinfo, tree, di, drep);
2489 }
2490 }
2491
2492 return offset;
2493}

2495/* Dissect an string of bytes. This corresponds to
2496 IDL of the form '[string] byte *foo'.
2497
2498 It can also be used for a conformant varying array of bytes if
2499 the contents of the array should be shown as a big blob, rather
2500 than showing each byte as an individual element.
2501
2502 XXX - which of those is really the IDL type for, for example,
2503 the encrypted data in some MAPI packets? (Microsoft hasn't
2504 released that IDL.)
2505
2506 XXX - does this need to do all the conformant array stuff that
2507 "dissect_ndr_ucvarray()" does? These are presumably for strings
2508 that are conformant and varying - they're stored like conformant
2509 varying arrays of bytes. */
2510int
2511dissect_ndr_byte_array(tvbuff_t *tvb, int offset, packet_info *pinfo,
2512 proto_tree *tree, dcerpc_info *di, guint8 *drep)
2513{
2514 guint64 len;
2515
2516 if (di->conformant_run) {
2517 /* just a run to handle conformant arrays, no scalars to dissect */
2518 return offset;
2519 }
2520
2521 /* NDR array header */
2522
2523 offset = dissect_ndr_uint3264(tvb, offset, pinfo, tree, di, drep,
2524 hf_dcerpc_array_max_count, NULL((void*)0));
2525
2526 offset = dissect_ndr_uint3264(tvb, offset, pinfo, tree, di, drep,
2527 hf_dcerpc_array_offset, NULL((void*)0));
2528
2529 offset = dissect_ndr_uint3264(tvb, offset, pinfo, tree, di, drep,
2530 hf_dcerpc_array_actual_count, &len);
2531
2532 DISSECTOR_ASSERT(len <= G_MAXUINT32)((void) ((len <= ((guint32) 0xffffffff)) ? (void)0 : (proto_report_dissector_bug
(wmem_strdup_printf(wmem_packet_scope(), "%s:%u: failed assertion \"%s\""
, "/home/remnux/Desktop/Thesis-Experiments/Third_Experiment/SAST_With_SRE/CVEs/CVE-2018-11360_Wireshark/Wireshark/epan/dissectors/packet-dcerpc.c"
, 2532, "len <= ((guint32) 0xffffffff)")))));
2533 if (len) {
2534 proto_tree_add_item(tree, di->hf_index, tvb, offset, (guint32)len,
2535 ENC_NA0x00000000);
2536 }
2537
2538 offset += (guint32)len;
2539
2540 return offset;
2541}

2545/* Dissect an NDR conformant varying string of elements.
2546 The length of each element is given by the 'size_is' parameter;
2547 the elements are assumed to be characters or wide characters.
2548
2549 XXX - does this need to do all the conformant array stuff that
2550 "dissect_ndr_ucvarray()" does? */
2551int
2552dissect_ndr_cvstring(tvbuff_t *tvb, int offset, packet_info *pinfo,
2553 proto_tree *tree, dcerpc_info *di, guint8 *drep, int size_is,
2554 int hfindex, gboolean add_subtree, char **data)
2555{
2556 header_field_info *hfinfo;
2557 proto_item *string_item;
2558 proto_tree *string_tree;
2559 guint64 len;
2560 guint32 buffer_len;
2561 char *s;
2562
2563 /* Make sure this really is a string field. */
2564 hfinfo = proto_registrar_get_nth(hfindex);
2565 DISSECTOR_ASSERT_FIELD_TYPE(hfinfo, FT_STRING)((void) (((hfinfo)->type == FT_STRING) ? (void)0 : (proto_report_dissector_bug
(wmem_strdup_printf(wmem_packet_scope(), "%s:%u: field %s is not of type "
"FT_STRING", "/home/remnux/Desktop/Thesis-Experiments/Third_Experiment/SAST_With_SRE/CVEs/CVE-2018-11360_Wireshark/Wireshark/epan/dissectors/packet-dcerpc.c"
, 2565, ((hfinfo))->abbrev)))));
2566
2567 if (di->conformant_run) {
2568 /* just a run to handle conformant arrays, no scalars to dissect */
2569 return offset;
2570 }
2571
2572 if (add_subtree) {
2573 string_tree = proto_tree_add_subtree(tree, tvb, offset, -1, ett_dcerpc_string, &string_item,
2574 proto_registrar_get_name(hfindex));
2575 } else {
2576 string_item = NULL((void*)0);
2577 string_tree = tree;
2578 }
2579
2580 /* NDR array header */
2581
2582 offset = dissect_ndr_uint3264(tvb, offset, pinfo, string_tree, di, drep,
2583 hf_dcerpc_array_max_count, NULL((void*)0));
2584
2585 offset = dissect_ndr_uint3264(tvb, offset, pinfo, string_tree, di, drep,
2586 hf_dcerpc_array_offset, NULL((void*)0));
2587
2588 offset = dissect_ndr_uint3264(tvb, offset, pinfo, string_tree, di, drep,
2589 hf_dcerpc_array_actual_count, &len);
2590
2591 /* The value is truncated to 32bits. 64bit values have only been
2592 seen on fuzztested files */
2593 buffer_len = size_is * (guint32)len;
2594
2595 /* Adjust offset */
2596 if (!di->no_align && (offset % size_is))
2597 offset += size_is - (offset % size_is);
2598
2599 /*
2600 * "tvb_get_string_enc()" throws an exception if the entire string
2601 * isn't in the tvbuff. If the length is bogus, this should
2602 * keep us from trying to allocate an immensely large buffer.
2603 * (It won't help if the length is *valid* but immensely large,
2604 * but that's another matter; in any case, that would happen only
2605 * if we had an immensely large tvbuff....)
2606 *
2607 * XXX - so why are we doing tvb_ensure_bytes_exist()?
2608 */
2609 tvb_ensure_bytes_exist(tvb, offset, buffer_len);
2610 if (size_is == sizeof(guint16)) {
2611 /*
2612 * Assume little-endian UTF-16.
2613 *
2614 * XXX - is this always little-endian?
2615 */
2616 s = tvb_get_string_enc(wmem_packet_scope(), tvb, offset, buffer_len,
2617 ENC_UTF_160x00000004|ENC_LITTLE_ENDIAN0x80000000);
2618 } else {
2619 /*
2620 * XXX - what if size_is is neither 1 nor 2?
2621 */
2622 s = tvb_get_string_enc(wmem_packet_scope(), tvb, offset, buffer_len,
2623 DREP_ENC_CHAR(drep)(((drep)[0] & 0x01) ? 0x0000002E|0x00000000 : 0x00000000|
0x00000000));
2624 }
2625 if (tree && buffer_len)
2626 proto_tree_add_string(string_tree, hfindex, tvb, offset,
2627 buffer_len, s);
2628
2629 if (string_item != NULL((void*)0))
2630 proto_item_append_text(string_item, ": %s", s);
2631
2632 if (data)
2633 *data = s;
2634
2635 offset += buffer_len;
2636
2637 proto_item_set_end(string_item, tvb, offset);
2638
2639 return offset;
2640}

2686/* This function is aimed for PIDL usage and dissects a UNIQUE pointer to
2687 * unicode string.
2688 */
2689int
2690PIDL_dissect_cvstring(tvbuff_t *tvb, int offset, packet_info *pinfo, proto_tree *tree, dcerpc_info *di, guint8 *drep, int chsize, int hfindex, guint32 param)
2691{
2692 char *s = NULL((void*)0);
2693 gint levels = CB_STR_ITEM_LEVELS(param)((param) & 0xFFFF);
2694
2695 offset = dissect_ndr_cvstring(tvb, offset, pinfo, tree, di, drep,
2696 chsize, hfindex,
2697 FALSE(0), &s);
2698
2699 if (!di->conformant_run) {
2700 /* Append string to COL_INFO */
2701 if (param & PIDL_SET_COL_INFO0x10000000) {
2702 col_append_fstr(pinfo->cinfo, COL_INFO, ", %s", s);
2703 }
2704 /* Save string to dcv->private_data */
2705 if ((param & PIDL_STR_SAVE0x20000000)
2706 && (!pinfo->fd->flags.visited)) {
2707 dcerpc_call_value *dcv = (dcerpc_call_value *)di->call_data;
2708 dcv->private_data = wmem_strdup(wmem_file_scope(), s);
2709 }
2710 /* Append string to upper-level proto_items */
2711 if ((levels > 0) && tree && s && s[0]) {
2712 proto_item_append_text(tree, ": %s", s);
2713 tree = tree->parent;
2714 levels--;
2715 if (levels > 0) {
2716 proto_item_append_text(tree, ": %s", s);
2717 tree = tree->parent;
2718 levels--;
2719 while (levels > 0) {
2720 proto_item_append_text(tree, " %s", s);
2721 tree = tree->parent;
2722 levels--;
2723 }
2724 }
2725 }
2726
2727 }
2728
2729 return offset;
2730}
